South Korean Ambassador to China Jang Ha-sungSouth Korea's new ambassador to China, Jang Ha-sung, vowed to maintain close strategic communication with China to resolve the Korean Peninsula issue and achieve permanent peace during his inauguration at the South Korean Embassy in Beijing on Monday, the Yonhap News Agency reported.Jang said he will work closely with China to promote communication and understanding, understand each other's positions in terms of empathy and patient listening, share development experiences, and expand exchanges and cooperation, the report said. Jang, a former top policy advisor to South Korean President Moon Jae-in, arrived in Beijing on Sunday, according to the Xinhua News Agency.Since Moon took office in May 2017, Jang served as presidential chief of staff for policy, a post to manage overall economic policy for the president, until November last year.Jang stressed that he will promote high-level exchanges and dialogues, including at the level of the two countries' leaders, and deepen strategic communication and mutual trust, adding that the trust between the leaders of the two countries will be the driving force for the development of the bilateral relations. In order to resolve the North Korean nuclear issue and achieve permanent peace on the peninsula, Jang noted that China needs to continuously play a constructive role, and that he will maintain close communication with China on this issue.Regarding economic cooperation between South Korea and China, Jang said that economic cooperation between the two countries needs to meet new models and open up a new era.Based on the huge changes in China's economic environment, and the experience accumulated by South Korean companies and emigrants, he will seek new areas and models of cooperation. He also stressed that he will work hard with China to cope with environmental problems such as air pollution, and strive to achieve concrete and tangible results.2019 marks the 100th anniversary of the Korean independence Sam-il (March 1) Movement and the establishment of the Provisional Government of the Republic of Korea. Jang said that he will take this opportunity to closely communicate with China and strive to achieve harmony and mutual benefit between Korea and China in all fields. China to be offered Russia's 'best warplane' Su-57New Zealand Prime Minister visits ChinaIndia's nationalistic media could disrupt China-India ties Seeing the futureAllahu Akbar